{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-blog-post-js","path":"/building-a-form-input-wave-takeaways/","result":{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"Stefi's Shorts","author":"Stefi Rosca"}},"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>I'm following <a style=\"color: #942874; text-decoration:underline\" target=\"blank\" href=\"https://twitter.com/florinpop1705\">Florin Pop</a> and <a style=\"color: #942874; text-decoration:underline\" target=\"blank\" href=\"https://twitter.com/traversymedia\">traversymedia</a> 50 Javascript, HTML, and CSS tutorials on Udemy. This is a great way to put into practice CSS properties I've learned but use rarely as well as do refresh some JavaScript DOM manipulation concepts.\nWhile going through the form-input-wave tutorial I got a better understanding on how some of the display properties work (inline, inline-block and block). I might write about this soon so do check back.</p>\n<p>Here are the 3 main takeaways:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>How one can create a span for each character of a word.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Simply by using the array split method from JS and adding the span around the element and then joining the word back using the join method, voila :) Here's the example of it:</p>\n<pre class=\"line-numbers\" style=\"background: #352d39; color:#e3f4f5; font-family: Open Sans,sans-serif;\">\n  <code class=\"language-markdown\">\n &lt;h1 class=\"title\" id=\"title\"&gt;Hello, world!&lt;/h1&gt;  \n &lt;script&gt;\n    const title = document.getElementById(\"title\");\n\ttitle.innerHTML = title.innerText\n     .split('')\n     .map((letter, index) => \n  \t\t`&lt;span \n              style=\"color:${\"#\"+Math.floor(Math.random()*16777215)\n                .toString(16)}\"&gt;${letter}&lt;/span&gt;`)\n \t\t\t    .join('')\n &lt;/script&gt;\n  </code>\n</pre>\n<pre class=\"line-numbers\" style=\"width:100%; background: #352d39; color:#e3f4f5; font-family: Open Sans,sans-serif;\">\n  <code class=\"language-markdown\">\n &lt;span style=\"color:${\"#\"+Math.floor(Math.random()*16777215)\n .toString(16)}\"&gt;${letter}&lt;/span&gt;\n  </code>\n</pre>\n<p>To make more of sense it I added in the <code>span</code> some inline style to generate a random color. I took the random color generating code from this <a style=\"color: #942874; text-decoration:underline\" target=\"blank\" href=\"https://dev.to/akhil_001/generating-random-color-with-single-line-of-js-code-fhj\">post</a>.</p>\n<p><b>Showcasing code with visual example:</b></p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 590px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/blog/static/75edc9c490a24ccd3021fa1bb16b8d20/39148/example-span-js.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 53.37837837837838%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Code with the example and visual side\"\n        title=\"Code with the example and visual side\"\n        src=\"/blog/static/75edc9c490a24ccd3021fa1bb16b8d20/fcda8/example-span-js.png\"\n        srcset=\"/blog/static/75edc9c490a24ccd3021fa1bb16b8d20/12f09/example-span-js.png 148w,\n/blog/static/75edc9c490a24ccd3021fa1bb16b8d20/e4a3f/example-span-js.png 295w,\n/blog/static/75edc9c490a24ccd3021fa1bb16b8d20/fcda8/example-span-js.png 590w,\n/blog/static/75edc9c490a24ccd3021fa1bb16b8d20/efc66/example-span-js.png 885w,\n/blog/static/75edc9c490a24ccd3021fa1bb16b8d20/c83ae/example-span-js.png 1180w,\n/blog/static/75edc9c490a24ccd3021fa1bb16b8d20/39148/example-span-js.png 2876w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>Besides this I've also learned about the propriety <code>pointer-events</code> and what happens when this is set to none.</p>\n<ol start=\"2\">\n<li>What <code>pointer-events:none;</code> can be used for.</span></li>\n</ol>\n<p>When we choose <code>pointer-events:none;</code> the element is never the target of a pointer event. The pointer will go \"through\" an element and target whatever is \"underneath\" that element instead. <a style=\"color: #942874; text-decoration:underline\" target=\"blank\" href=\"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/pointer-events\">*source</a></p>\n<p>This was needed as the label was initial set on the input box and it was hard to select the input otherwise. You can see that per the <code>position:absolute;</code>.</p>\n<pre class=\"line-numbers\" style=\"max-width=300px; background: #352d39; color:#e3f4f5; font-family: Open Sans,sans-serif\">\n  <code class=\"language-css\">\n  .form-control label {\n    position: absolute;\n    top: 15px;\n    left: 0px;\n    pointer-events: none;\n}\n    </code>\n</pre>\n<p>In the picture below one can see that the labe is on the input field which is exactly where the line is. Therefore if there would be no <code>pointer-events: none;</code> one would not be able to select with the pointer the input field when clicking on Email.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 590px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/blog/static/8c843f06417dfb25014adf79eeec2609/fdaf8/example-1.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 50%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Example 1 with label on the input field\"\n        title=\"Example 1 with label on the input field\"\n        src=\"/blog/static/8c843f06417dfb25014adf79eeec2609/fcda8/example-1.png\"\n        srcset=\"/blog/static/8c843f06417dfb25014adf79eeec2609/12f09/example-1.png 148w,\n/blog/static/8c843f06417dfb25014adf79eeec2609/e4a3f/example-1.png 295w,\n/blog/static/8c843f06417dfb25014adf79eeec2609/fcda8/example-1.png 590w,\n/blog/static/8c843f06417dfb25014adf79eeec2609/fdaf8/example-1.png 674w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>In example 2 we can see that once the field is selected the label goes up as we set it with CSS in the project. I will highlight this next.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 590px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/blog/static/cb5842a4ab89dedc82b4ad83f5a8737a/38cea/example-2.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 62.83783783783784%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Example 2 label moves above the input field\"\n        title=\"Example 2 label moves above the input field\"\n        src=\"/blog/static/cb5842a4ab89dedc82b4ad83f5a8737a/fcda8/example-2.png\"\n        srcset=\"/blog/static/cb5842a4ab89dedc82b4ad83f5a8737a/12f09/example-2.png 148w,\n/blog/static/cb5842a4ab89dedc82b4ad83f5a8737a/e4a3f/example-2.png 295w,\n/blog/static/cb5842a4ab89dedc82b4ad83f5a8737a/fcda8/example-2.png 590w,\n/blog/static/cb5842a4ab89dedc82b4ad83f5a8737a/38cea/example-2.png 678w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<ol start=\"3\">\n<li>Move up the label of a input field by a certain measure using the <code>transform</code> propriety.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>In order to do this one would use the transform property <code>translateY</code> and give it a negative value. It's Y as it is on the Y axis and negative so it goes up.</p>\n<pre class=\"line-numbers\" style=\"max-width=300px; background: #352d39; color:#e3f4f5; font-family: Open Sans,sans-serif\">\n  <code class=\"language-css\">\n    .form-control input:focus + label span,\n    .form-control input:valid + label span {\n        color: #91cbed;\n        transform: translateY(-48px);\n}\n    </code>\n</pre>\n<p>That's all for now! Thanks for reading 🙈</p>\n<p><a style=\"color: #942874; text-decoration:underline\" target=\"blank\" href=\"https://stefi.xyz/50-JS-Projects/form-input-wave/index.html \">Project preview</a></p>","frontmatter":{"title":"3 Things I've learned by building the form-input-wave project","tags":["coding","css"],"categories":"coding","date":"December 26, 2020","featuredImage":{"childImageSharp":{"sizes":{"src":"/blog/static/75edc9c490a24ccd3021fa1bb16b8d20/2a4de/example-span-js.png"}}}},"excerpt":"I'm following Florin Pop and traversymedia 50 Javascript, HTML, and CSS tutorials on Udemy. This is a great way to put into practice CSS…","fields":{"slug":"/building-a-form-input-wave-takeaways/"},"timeToRead":3}},"pageContext":{}}}